"It's 2:00 AM, and you're the on-call DevOps Engineer. A production application hosted on a Linux server has suddenly become very slow, and users are reporting timeouts. You cannot simply restart the server. How would you troubleshoot the issue?"

My Approach

1️⃣ Check the overall system health

uptime
top
htop

Verify CPU utilization.
Check the load average.
Identify processes consuming excessive resources.

2️⃣ Check memory utilization
free -h
vmstat 1 5
Verify available memory.
Check whether the server is swapping heavily.

3️⃣ Verify disk usage
df -h
du -sh /*
Ensure no filesystem has reached 100% utilization.
Identify directories consuming excessive disk space.

4️⃣ Identify resource-intensive processes
ps aux --sort=-%cpu
ps aux --sort=-%mem
Find processes consuming abnormal CPU or memory.

5️⃣ Review system and application logs
journalctl -xe
tail -100 /var/log/syslog
Look for service failures, kernel messages, or application errors.

6️⃣ Verify network connectivity
ss -tulnp
curl localhost:<port>
Confirm the application is listening on the expected port.
Verify the service is responding locally. 

7️⃣ Check critical services
systemctl status nginx
systemctl status docker
systemctl status kubelet
Verify that required services are healthy before taking any action.

Key Takeaway

In production, restarting the server should be the last option—not the first.

A DevOps Engineer's responsibility is to:

Gather evidence.
Identify the root cause.
Validate the findings.
Implement the appropriate fix while minimizing downtime.

This structured troubleshooting approach helps resolve incidents efficiently and prevents recurring issues.
